The paper discusses cyber security from a defensive perspective and proposes the use of cybernetics, control theory, systems theory, information theory, and game theory as foundational approaches for developing cyber security principles. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the principles for building non-stationary systems, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY). The paper also mentions game theory, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of Game Theory and Decision Science (cs.GT). Additionally, the paper mentions information theory, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of Information Theory (cs.IT). Lastly, the paper discusses related works concerning the limitations of moving target defense and one implementation based on non-stationary principles, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Software Engineering (cs.SE).
